			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">How exactly does an angel or demon fit in with the whole "master of the elements" theme of our pets? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
It doesn't, and I don't particularly care.  I think the "master of elements" themes behind our pets limits rather than inspires creativity.  Limiting class development to marketing words tossed out by some writer back at the beginning of EQ does not strike me as a very good idea.  I am basing these ideas on the game mechanics as they exist and have developed over time, and on the simplest concept of being a magician which is summoning or creation.  Any "master of elements" explanation can be again traced back to more general "summoning" or "conjuration." 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The 4 elemental pets are good enough for mages, and I can't see a use for any other pets that wouldn't be over powering or infringe on another class. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I just gave at least one clear example of a pet that wouldn't be overpowering nor would it significantly infringe on another class:  A pet that dealt no damage but instead procced heal spells on the target.  It would be a totally unique magician ability, at least so far as I know.  No class can randomly proc heals on another target, and most certianly no pet can.  It would not generally not replace healers in xp groups.  At worst, it would ease the "requirement" of the tank-healing combination.  Without a real healer you would still suck in emergencies.
<br />

<br />
Ok, I hate the way tradeskills work in EQ and would never want a significant class ability dependant on them, at least no more dependant than any other droppable item.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Here's how it'd work in my mind. You create the base golem, when you do this you get an item that has unlimited charges (or gives you a hotkey like AA do) that summons a lvl 1 golem. This creation would be very expensive and requiree a high research skill along with JC, pottery, and smithing. JC used to create the item that binds the golem to your control, pottery to create the general form of the golem, smithing to create the armor and weapons of the golem, and finally research to animate the golem. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Not to be rude, but this sounds to me like nothing more than a huge hassle.  At best, it would be a bunch of garbage that I would have to go spend tons of plat on, at worst, I'd have to do all the fricking tradeskills myself.  If EQ tradeskills weren't mindless clickathons, this would be cool.  If there was something <span style="font-style: italic">to</span> tradeskills other than the small feeling of elation when you finally create something, it would be cool.  Or if they had done someting like this for beastlords instead of the pets they gave them, making them a sort of "tradeskill class" from the start, that would have been cool too.  Otherwise, no, leave tradeskills completely optional, or as minor compenents at best.  Don't turn mages into a fricking tradeskill class I gaurantee you people would be really pissed off.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Just like the eye, caster can control it, it is indiferrent to all, but Unlike eye it lasts 2 times as long, and all members of the group can see through it, and more importantly CAST through it. Group members should be able to target indivitually though it. Any aggro generated by the eye by anyone in the group is atrributed to the mage. (Gotta be a downside, and this is the best one I can think if.) </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This is a neat idea, but don't just try to make up a random downside for no reason.  The downside actually makes sense, but downsides should make the game more interesting and fun whenever possible-- they should not simply be hassles to put up with because otherwise you'd be too powerful.
<br />

<br />
But this ability, while it seems cool, I think it would wind up being used for little more than the reason you mentioned, which was to pacify rooms at no danger to the group.  I don't think EQ really needs that at this point.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Ask for the overpowering. Ask for exactly what you want. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I don't want overpowering.  I want interesting.  I want fun.  I want unique abilties that other classes won't have.  Fun != a pet that can solo everything in the game.  That = boring.  Well, it would be fun for about 2 weeks until you realized that a game with no challenge pretty much sucks.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In all of the time that we try to come up with an equal and balanced idea does Sony ever develop it in that way? No, they develop a scaled back version if they develop it at all.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Scaled back like what?  Pre-nerf T-Rods?  Those were plenty (over)powerful, they were so powerful that the vast amounts of time raiding as a magician was spent doing the most god-awful boring thing you can imagine.  Yes, worse than CH loops.  Yes, worse than being pestered for haste from melees.  Mages got to sit in the corner and drop T-Rods on the ground.  They would drop.. rod, after rod, after rod, after rod, after rod, after rod, after rod...     That was super, like Homer Simpson on disability!  Mages were SO powerful, <span style="font-style: italic">no one could raid</span> without mages!  
<br />

<br />
I'll say this, there is small limit to the <span style="font-style: italic">relative</span>, <span style="font-style: italic">raw</span> power I'd give to mages.  If mages are the supreme damage dealing class in the game, I would not care if the other classes complained-- so long as mage power was fun to use and didn't <span style="font-style: italic">invalidate</span> other classes.
<br />

<br />
Ideas get changed when ideas suck.  If you ask for the stars and get a photo of Van Gogh's <span style="font-style: italic">Starry Starry Night</span>, you have no one to blame but yourself for making such an absurd request.  It usually looks like ideas get "scaled back" because players will almost invariably ask for too much power.  On the other hand if a player comes up with a good idea and loads on a lot of useless nerfs because he thinks they're necessary, a dev would happily surprise the users with a more powerful version.  They've done it before.  Over the span of a month or two we saw them <span style="font-style: italic">removing variable pet levels, increasing pet damage, ending pet mez-breakage, and making pets indifferent to all</span>.  During that time did we get nerfed AT ALL?  No, despite the fact that there were plenty of arguments on the table for why we <span style="font-style: italic">should not</span> have had all those things handed to us on a silver platter.
<br />

<br />
So on one hand, yes, do not waste too much time trying to nerf things or being so diffident that the intent of your ideas suffer.  On the other hand don't waste time asking for anything ridiculously overpowered that has no merit other than being overpowered, because it will be ignored.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
